[{"id":"FT575768","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<p>Which of the following pedigrees most accurately represents a family with a history of Tay-Sachs disease?</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<img alt=\"The figure presents a key for the following answer choices. The key indicates that an unshaded square represents an unaffected male an unshaded circle represents an unaffected female a shaded square represents an affected male and a shaded circle represents an affected female.\" height=\"213\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/media.academicmerit.com/1a368b2c45afdd316807f1eb9408cb32/original.png\" width=\"285\" />","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<p>Tay-Sachs disease is a rare inherited disorder caused by an autosomal recessive allele of the <em>HEXA</em> gene. Affected individuals exhibit severe neurological symptoms and do not survive to reproductive age. Individuals who inherit one copy of the allele (Tay-Sachs carriers) typically show no symptoms of the disorder. The frequencies of Tay-Sachs carriers in the general population of North America and in three different subpopulations are presented in the table.</p>\n\n<p><img alt=\"The table shows the frequency of Tay-Sachs Carriers in different populations. For general population the frequency is 0.004. For subpopulation 1 the frequency is 0.037. For subpopulation 2 the frequency is 0.035. For subpopulation 3 the frequency is 0.020.\" height=\"227\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/media.academicmerit.com/971a5f290154de6aa80c2d170d9642cd/original.png\" width=\"455\" /></p>\n"}],"choicesHtml":["<img alt=\"The figure presents a pedigree with three generations. In the first generation, an affected male and an affected female have the following five children as part of the second generation: an unaffected male, two affected males, and two affected females. The second generation unaffected male has the following three children with an unaffected female: an unaffected male and two unaffected females. One of the second generation affected females has the following four children with an unaffected male: two affected males and two unaffected females.\" height=\"99\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/media.academicmerit.com/4ed00e1b64abc5b474cc008596d46dec/original.png\" width=\"200\">","<img alt=\"The figure presents a pedigree with three generations. An unaffected male and an unaffected female have the following five children as part of the second generation: two unaffected males, an affected male, an unaffected female and an affected female. One of the second generation unaffected males has the following three children with an unaffected female: an unaffected male and two unaffected females. The second generation unaffected female has the following four children with an unaffected male: two unaffected males and two unaffected females. \" height=\"95\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/media.academicmerit.com/25345bfc9db2b41270925fad85e60ee4/original.png\" width=\"200\">","<img alt=\"The figure presents a pedigree with three generations. An unaffected male and an affected female have the following five children as part of the second generation: three affected males and two affected females. One of the second generation affected males has the following three children with an unaffected female: an unaffected male and two unaffected females. One of the second generation affected females has the following four children with an unaffected male: two affected males and two affected females.\" height=\"93\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/media.academicmerit.com/b1802ba227a8e83560e06b9fc1835f58/original.png\" width=\"200\">","<img alt=\"The figure presents a pedigree with three generations. An affected male and an unaffected female have the following five children as part of the second generation: an affected male an unaffected male, an affected female, and two unaffected females. The second generation affected male has the following three children with an unaffected female: an affected male and two unaffected females. The second generation affected female has the following four children with an unaffected male: an affected male, an unaffected male, an affected female, and an unaffected female.\" height=\"94\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/media.academicmerit.com/46602d71b65794f8d5c602ad81ee5d4d/original.png\" width=\"200\">"],"answer":0}]